`scripts/` is the collection of CI/lint checks and doc-generators invoked
by `ctx-verify`'s battery and by manual doc regeneration — each script is
a standalone bash/python check that either exits nonzero with `FAIL:`
lines on stderr, or (for the two `gen_*` scripts) rewrites a marked block
in a doc and supports `--check`/`--write` symmetry.

All the `*_check.sh` lint scripts share one enumeration contract: file
discovery goes through `git ls-files -z --cached --others
--exclude-standard`, never a filesystem walk, so results are a pure
function of git state and don't race concurrent `target/` writes or scan
gitignored paths. They also share an output contract: failures are
`FAIL: path:line: message` lines on stderr, produced via `grep -nHF ...
-- files /dev/null` (the trailing `/dev/null` forces multi-file
`path:line:` prefixing) so ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser can extract
`path:line` uniformly — any new check script must follow this shape or
ctx-verify's parser breaks silently. `no_allow_check.sh` and
`retired_terms_check.sh` are explicit siblings on this pattern;
`workspace_lints_check.sh` and `machete_check.sh` follow the same git
enumeration but with awk-based parsing of tool-specific output.

`cycle_check.sh` and `rationale_check.py` are both explicit MVP
placeholders deferring real logic to future dylint rules (see
`docs/DYLINT_RULES.md`) — cycle_check never actually detects cycles yet,
rationale_check uses brace-heuristics instead of an AST. `machete_check.sh`
and `no_allow_check.sh`/`retired_terms_check.sh` differ in failure
philosophy: machete/no_allow/retired_terms hard-fail on missing tools or
git-tree violations (no graceful skip), since their entire job is a
negative assertion that would otherwise silently pass.

`gen_readme_architecture.sh` and `gen_tool_contracts.sh` both rewrite
marked blocks in docs using paired `BEGIN GENERATED .../END GENERATED`
markers and an awk-based `committed_block` extractor plus in-place
splice; both require pre-existing markers (hard-fail if absent) and both
support `--check` (accumulate `FAIL=1`, keep going) vs `--write` (exit 1
immediately on error). `gen_tool_contracts.sh` additionally depends on
four binaries' `--contract` flag as a de facto wire format — changing
that output requires re-running `--write`.